# BrickLayer + Masonry + Mortar — Architecture

## The Three-Layer Model

```
Claude Code
     ↕
  Masonry          ← the device/bridge (MCP server, hooks, routing engine, schemas)
     ↕
 BrickLayer        ← the layer alongside Claude Code (research loop, campaigns, sims, agent fleet)
```

**BrickLayer** lives alongside Claude Code. It is the full framework: research campaigns, simulations, agent fleet, findings, synthesis. It is NOT a subprocess — it's a parallel layer.

**Masonry** is the device that communicates between BrickLayer and Claude Code. It is the bridge: MCP server, hooks, typed payload schemas, routing engine, DSPy optimization. When Claude Code needs BrickLayer or vice versa, Masonry carries the message.

**Mortar** is the master executor. Every request — coding, research, git, docs, UI, campaigns, anything — lands at Mortar first. Mortar reads the request, decides the right agents, and dispatches in parallel. All agents report to Mortar.

## Mortar Is the Entry Point for Everything

**Every request goes through Mortar** (exception: single-sentence factual lookups — see Operating Principles). Mortar splits work to:

| Work Type | Mortar dispatches to |
|-----------|----------------------|
| Coding task | rough-in → queen-coordinator → workers (parallel, up to 8) |
| Research question | research-analyst + competitive-analyst + others (parallel) |
| Campaign / simulation | Trowel (owns the full BL 2.0 loop) |
| Git hygiene | git-nerd |
| Folder organization / project structure | karen |
| UI / design | uiux-master |
| Architecture decisions | architect or design-reviewer |
| Debugging unknown failure | diagnose-analyst |
| Security review | security agent |
| Spec + build | spec-writer → developer pipeline |

**Never do complex work solo when Mortar can dispatch a team.**

## Core Behavior Rules

- **The prompt-router hook routes every request** — dev tasks → rough-in directly, campaigns → mortar, specialists → named agent
- **Parallel by default** — independent tasks always dispatched simultaneously
- **After any code changes** → git-nerd proactively handles commits and branch hygiene
- **Messy project state** → karen audits and organizes without being asked
- **Campaigns/sims** → Mortar hands to Trowel; Trowel owns that loop end-to-end
- **Dev tasks** → Rough-in decomposes, Queen Coordinator dispatches up to 8 workers in parallel

## Operating Principles

- **Never resume an autopilot build** (`/build`, `/fix`, `/ultrawork`) from a prior session — surface the state and ask
- Delegate specialist work to agents — multi-file implementations, debugging, reviews, planning
- Prefer evidence over assumptions — verify outcomes before claiming completion
- Lightest path that preserves quality — direct action ONLY for single-sentence factual lookups (e.g., "what port does X run on?") and clarification questions that require no tool use and no multi-step reasoning. All other work routes through the prompt-router hook which directs to the right specialist.
- Consult docs (context7) before implementing with unfamiliar SDKs or APIs
- Run independent tasks in parallel — use multiple Agent calls in a single message

## Agent Routing

Pass `model` to match complexity: `haiku` quick lookups · `sonnet` standard work · `opus` architecture/deep analysis

For codebase exploration use `subagent_type: "Explore"`. **Never reference oh-my-claudecode — it is uninstalled.**

> **Mortar uses four-layer routing** (deterministic → semantic → LLM → fallback). Deterministic handles 60%+ of routing with zero LLM calls. See `mortar.md` for details.

